## Pillar 3: Strategic Commenting

### When to trigger this section
User says: "draft a comment", "comment template", "what to comment on", "commenting strategy", "influencer posts"

### Target Accounts to Follow & Comment On

**Indian PM / Product Leaders**
- Shreyas Doshi — product strategy, prioritization, PM career
- Ravi Mehta — growth, consumer products
- Nikhyl Singhal — career, senior PM, leadership

**AI Builders & Researchers (Global)**
- Andrej Karpathy — AI/ML, LLMs
- Ethan Mollick — AI adoption, practical AI use
- Harrison Chase — LangChain, agentic workflows
- Simon Willison — LLM tools, practical AI

**Indian Startup Ecosystem**
- Active CPOs/founders at Series A–D companies in India
- Recruiters at target companies (comment = warm intro)

### Comment Quality Bar
A comment must be good enough to stand alone as a mini-post.
**Never:** "Great post!" / "So true!" / "Thanks for sharing!"
**Always:** Add a POV, pushback, example from your own work, or sharp follow-up question

### Comment Templates

**Template 1 — Add a real example from your work**
```
[Restate their point in 1 line] — I ran into exactly this at [abstract context, not "ambulance company"].

We [specific decision you made]. The result was [outcome].

The part I'd add: [your additional insight or nuance they missed].
```

**Template 2 — Respectful pushback**
```
Strong point, but I'd push back slightly on [specific claim].

In my experience [concrete situation], [what you observed] — which suggests [alternative view].

Curious if you've seen the same or if this is domain-specific.
```

**Template 3 — Build on their idea with a product angle**
```
This maps directly to [product concept / framework].

The way I've applied it: [1–2 sentence specific example].

The open question I haven't solved: [genuine question]. Anyone cracked this?
```

**Template 4 — For recruiter posts (job openings, hiring content)**
```
[Engaging observation about what they're building / the problem space].

This is exactly the type of [challenge / system / product] I've been working on — [1-line relevant experience].

Would love to connect and learn more about [specific aspect of their work].
```

### Commenting Rules
- Never use Abhishek's company name (Red Health) in comments — keep it domain-neutral
- Reference the *problem or system* not the industry (e.g., "multi-agent dispatch" not "ambulance dispatch")
- Max 4–5 lines per comment. Shorter is almost always better.
- Respond to replies within 2 hours when active — comment threads drive reach

